<!a href="/townhall/columnists/weyrich.html"><!Biography>

<p>


<h3>
June 4, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
An Old Dog Learns New Tricks
</h2>
<P>
<P>An Old Dog Learns New Tricks
<P>Ever since Bob Dole became Senate Majority Leader in 1985 I have had a running argument with him. I often told Dole to bring measures to the floor of the Senate for a vote, regardless of whether or not you have enough Senators willing to pass the bills. By losing, you win. Those votes would reveal the liberals for what they are and help elect more conservatives to the Senate.<P>
Dole disagreed. He didn’t want to vote on anything unless he thought he had the votes to pass it. That is why he and his chief of staff Sheila Burke always sought the lowest common denominator legislation. The less controversial, the better the chance to rack up a big win. Of course, the less controversial, the less chance of accomplishing anything with the legislation. Historic opportunities were lost in many fields because the legislation Dole usually got passed was so bipartisan that it demonstrated no differences between the parties. I argued that without this contrast, voters would have no incentive to add to Dole’s ranks. He never seemed to get it, that is, until now.<P>
There is a great irony in the way Bob Dole will finish out his last week as the Senate Republican Leader. He will bring up measures, including the Balanced Budget Amendment to the Constitution, which have no chance of passage. In doing so, Dole will be trying to get across to the American voters some of the main differences between the parties. Dole has dared President Clinton to help get the last two votes needed to pass the Balanced Budget Amendment through the Senate. However, the President opposes the Balanced Budget Amendment to the Constitution. <P>
Who says you can’t teach an old dog new tricks? Dole now seems to understand, albeit during the last moments of his Senate Leadership, that you can win by losing. I honestly believe, had this been done more of the time, with thorough preparation and lots of prolonged debate, the public would finally see who was on which side of the different debates and would act accordingly at the next election. The fact that meaningless bipartisan, vanilla legislation would pass the Senate by big margins only served to confuse the electorate. All sides could take credit for almost nothing. No wonder so many incumbents were re-elected. <P>
Now at the eleventh hour Dole is going to lose in the Senate in a very high profile way. But in losing he may gain points with the American voter.<P>
Although Dole has seemed to learn something new at this last moment, in some things he is sticking to the past. Chief of Staff Sheila Burke, it seems, may end up in the Dole campaign after all. <P>
Some, such as American Conservative Union Chairman David Keene, say this just proves Bob Dole is loyal to his friends. Perhaps. I think it proves that Bob Dole does not believe he can get along without Sheila Burke after having become so dependent on her over these last few years. Keene says that Sheila Burke never pursued her own agenda, but rather she served Bob Dole by doing exactly what he wanted done. If that is the case, then Dole is, indeed, a lot more liberal than his voting record suggests. <P>
At any rate, we will soon learn the truth. Since Dole’s announced resignation from the Senate, the Dole campaign seems to have found new life and has begun to develop a consistent message. If Sheila Burke is truly the team player her defenders claim she is, she will go along with all of it and blend right in. Then Sheila, old Senate dog that she is, will have learned new tricks too. <P>
On the other hand, if Sheila behaves as she has over the past years in Dole’s office, she will begin to impose herself on various aspects of the campaign. If you read news accounts about how Burke is trying to get the Republican platform liberalized, then you will understand that it is the same old Sheila at work. And if David Keene is correct, she will be doing so at Dole’s bidding. <P>
I’m encouraged that Dole has finally caught on to how you can win in the long run by losing in the short run. Now let’s see if his new found wisdom rubs off on Sheila. Hope springs eternal, as the saying goes. <P>


<blockquote>
<p>

<P>
<blockquote>
