<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<br>[ <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a> | <a href="/townhall/columnists/weyrich/i-date.html">Previous Commentaries</a> | <a href="/townhall/columnists/">Columnists</a> ] 
<h3>
May 28, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Clinton Should Stay Out of Foreign Elections"
</h2>
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>
<P>
By this time tomorrow we may know the projected winner in the Israeli elections. 
<P>By all measures, the contest will be determined by a razor-thin margin. The choice for Prime Minister is between the incumbent Shimon Peres and the challenger Benjamin Netanyahu. But in a sense, it is a contest between the old political order and a new order where the outcome depends largely on teenagers voting for the first time and refugees from the former Soviet Union who are also participating in their first Israeli election. 
<P>It has been an interesting roller coaster of an election. Netanyahu was chosen by the opposition Likud bloc last year and immediately began to challenge the so called peace process supported by the late Prime Minister Yitzak Rabin. Netanyahu jumped to a substantial lead in the polls and there was talk that Rabin was finished politically. Indeed the rally at which Rabin was shot was being held to drum up political support for the sagging fortunes of Rabin. 
<P>When Foreign Minister Shimon Peres took over from Rabin and the media tried to blame Netanyahu for creating the climate which led to Rabin’s death, Peres took what seemed to be an insurmountable lead in the polls. But Arab terrorist attacks and the ineffective Israeli response to them has permitted Netanyahu to climb back, inch by inch, to the point that he is now in a statistical dead heat with Peres and may even be slightly ahead with only 2% of the vote still undecided. 
<P>The outcome in this election will have an impact here in Washington. Throughout our history, we have always had our favorites in foreign elections. Hints were dropped here and there about what Washington thought and there were subtle moves to indicate our preference. But this time, President Bill Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, and other Administration officials have gone full tilt for Peres. At the moment polls showed the election tightening, Clinton called a hastily improvised summit meeting with Peres which was nothing more than a photo opportunity for the commercials which are now running on Israeli television. Of course promises of more foreign aid to Israel were suggested, IF Peres is re-elected. 
<P>The Clinton Administration in word and deed has left no stone unturned in its effort to influence the Israeli voters who know full well that there would be no Israel at all were it not for America. They also know how dependent Israel is on American economic aid so when "big brother" says he wants Peres, it is politically significant. But it may have backfired on Clinton and if so, the price to be paid will be high. 
<P>I had discussions with Netanyahu some years ago when he served in Washington. He is one tough customer. In fact, he may be the bluntest politician running for any office anywhere in the world. He would have no hesitancy in facing down Clinton and company the way he has faced down all of his domestic political enemies, which are many. 
<P>The Arabs, who have found common ground with Peres, would find that they had quite another kind of politician to deal with if Netanyahu wins. The Arabs who are eligible to vote in the Israeli elections are backing Peres nearly unanimously. 
<P>Directly interfering in a foreign election is not only a big gamble, it goes against the democratic principles we claim we espouse. This is an election for the citizens of Israel to decide, not for Washington to dictate.
<P>The United States is also intervening similarly in the Russian elections where we have done everything but carry the suitcases for Boris Yeltsin. Indeed our involvement has become one of the principal issues in the elections. Gregory Yavilinsky, who is the one candidate who comes closest to professing the democratic and free market ideals we claim to stand for, is outraged because until the United States and its Western partner intervened massively for Yeltsin, he was thought to have a shot at the election. That intervention, done at the taxpayer’s expense, may have propped up Yeltsin but it has also played right into the hand of the leading candidate, Gennady Zyuganov, whose main issue is that a plot on the part of the West caused the Soviet Union to collapse and thus it must be restored. 
<P>Bill Clinton has proved to be a masterful politician when it comes to handling the Republican Congress. With the media as his ally, he seems to be galloping to a second term and perhaps taking the Congress with him. His opponents claim he is guilty of deception and political manipulation. Be that as it may, Bill Clinton ought to stick to campaigning in this country. His overt intervention in foreign elections is dangerous either way those elections go. 
<P>Bill Clinton and company are big supporters of the New World Order so they see it as their duty to intervene. But the American taxpayers have no such obligation and through our elected officials in Congress we ought to demand that this worldwide manipulation of the democratic process be stopped before it drags us headlong into another world war.<P>

<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
