<TITLE>Paul Weyrich's Dateline Washington</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<center>
<img src="dateline.gif">
<h3>
May 8, 1996
</h3>
<h2>
"Washington’s Misplaced Perspective"
</h2>
(Delivered by Brad Keena)
</center>
<blockquote>
<P>

<P>
	There is old adage that says "politics is like sausage – you don't want to know how it is made!"
	Considering this is an election year, each passing day is proving those words were inspired to describe Washington and its establishment.  Washington today is like a great big sausage factory.  Broadcasting here so close to the factory, we sense it all around us.  Even now, as I listen carefully, I can hear the haunting screams of ordinary citizens falling into giant tax machines ripping out their wallets; tossing what remains in huge grinders designed to pulverize faith and morality through the terrible engines of an unstoppable federal judiciary.  In the air this election year is the malodorous waft of this huge sausage factory we call Washington.  The mixture created in this factory is ghastly to look at until the Administration adds its coloring to give the final grind an appearance of being edible.
<P>	Like short-order cooks, the establishment media fries up this nasty glop into bite size bits, served on plates with ugly china patterns with names like HUD, Education, Commerce, and Labor.
The table is set before the hungry establishment elite competing in a sausage-eating contest – a game which will last until November.  No one at the table is willing to admit where the sausage came from, how it is made, or what's in it.  To admit this would cause each at the table to lose his or her appetite:  for the sausage has come from outside of Washington.  It has been scandalously and horribly made with the most vile additives.  Its ingredients include the faith and hopes and dreams of ordinary Americans.  Together the future of each has been reprocessed into morsels prepared for the gluttonous elite seated at Washington's table.
<P>	The machine grinds on.  The terrible sounds continue night and day.  The stench of this factory permeates the air.  Unending is the Establishment's voracious appetite for power over its citizenry.
Perspective is a remarkable thing.  As humans, we tend to get lost in the false perspective of seeming permanence.  Time is slow moving.  Often we think what we see at the moment is permanent, but we're wrong.  America did not always look this way.  We have allowed our own government to remove itself from morality's scale.  The courts have overruled God's moral measurements, the government has thrown aside God's ethical scales.  The true measurement is sure.  It's weight is exact.  It's precision remains for all time.  Yet our culture has chosen a perspective which avoids to close a look at the moral and ethical realities.  Don't ask, don't tell about homosexuality in the military; don't ask, don't tell about the murder of babies even moments before birth; don't ask, don't tell about a political process promising to deliver everything we want at the expense of everything we've got.
<P>	This is not America.  This is another nation.  It's capital has become the sausage factory.  
In the banquet hall, its king and his lords, his wives and his concubines are drinking the blood of society in silver vessels, praising the gods of the Establishment.  On one wall of Washington's terrible banquet hall is a great hand.  It is writing Washington's future, telling the measurement and weight of the moral scales society had allowed Washington to disregard.  The writing on this wall is becoming visible for all to see:  "Moral integrity has been found wanting. Days are numbered. The kingdom is about to become divided."
<P>	Meanwhile, the banquet continues.  The writing on the wall has gone yet unnoticed.  The Washington sausage factory drones on.<P>


<P>
<blockquote>
<a href="http://net.fcref.org"><img src="netgif.gif" border="0" align ="right"></a><i>Dateline Washington: by Paul Weyrich is broadcast live weeknights at 6:00pm during <b>Direct Line with Paul Weyrich</b> on NET.
</blockquote> 	
