<title>What A Balanced Federal Budget with Tax Cuts Would Mean to the Economy -- Heritage</title>
<body><center>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">

<h3><i>WHAT A BALANCED FEDERAL BUDGET WITH TAX CUTS
WOULD MEAN TO THE ECONOMY</i></h3>

<a href="/heritage/staff/beach.htm">William W. Beach</a><br>
Visiting Fellow in Tax Analysis<br>
and<br>
John S. Barry<br>
Economics Research Assistant<br>
<p>
<a href="/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
Presentation to Senate Republican Conference<br>
November 15, 1995<br>
<hr width=50%></center>
<p>
<a href="#graphs">Graphs and Charts</a>
<p>
Using a generally accepted and widely regarded model of the U.S. economy, we found that balancing the federal budget between 1996 and 2002 while cutting taxes caused the economy generally to grow more than not balancing the budget and cutting taxes.
<p>
<i>Specifically, according to the simulation, the balanced budget plan with tax relief would mean:</i>
<p><ul>
<li>Gross Domestic Product grows by $10.8 billion more than under current law in the year 2002.
<p>
<li>An additional $32.1 billion in real disposable income over the period 1995 through 2002.
<p>
<li>An additional $66.2 billion in consumption expenditures over the period 1995 though 2002.
<p>
<li>An additional $88.2 billion in real non-residential fixed investment over the period 1995 through 2002.
<p>
<li>A decrease of 0.4 percent in the conventional mortgage rate.  This means that a balanced budget with tax relief would save a home borrower of $100,000 about $10,000 over the life of a 30-year mortgage.
<P>
<li>The additional construction of 104,000 new family homes over the next seven years.
<p>
<li>The additional sales of 600,000 automobiles over the next seven years worth $10 billion.
<p>
<li>A decrease of 0.7 percent in the growth rate of the Consumer Price Index.
<p></ul>
	The Heritage Foundation used the U.S. economic model developed by Laurence H. Meyer & Associates, a nationally recognized economic consulting company, to reach these conclusions. Laurence H. Meyer & Associates are consultants to many government agencies including the Office of Management & Budget, the Federal Reserve Board, the Department of Labor, the Congressional Budget Office, and the Council of Economic Advisors.
<p>
	Heritage made no changes to the Meyer model except to reset federal spending levels to mirror those contained in the Congressional Budget Resolution of May and to reduce tax rates that capture tax policy changes defined by the Senate Finance Committee.  We explicitly continued the assumption of the Meyer model that the Federal Reserve would not act to stimulate the economy in the face of slower than expected growth.  Had we allowed the model to use the assumption of a more active Federal Reserve, all of the numbers reported below would have been significantly higher.
<p>
Specifically, we assumed:
<p><ul>
<li>Reductions in the rate of growth for Medicare and Medicaid follow those in the budget resolution.
<p>
<li>Cash aid welfare spending growth rates were capped at 3.5 percent.
<P>
<li>Increases in national defense spending were applied primarily to Department of Defense procurement programs.
<p>
<li>All other spending -- for government purchases and transfer payments -- was reduced in the same proportion called for in the budget resolution until balance was reached in 2002.
<p>
<li>A 50 percent exemption of capital gains was assumed through 2004.
<p>
<li>Family tax relief and other provisions of the Senate tax package were accounted for by changing the effective tax rates on wages, dividends, and individuals.
</ul><p>
<hr>

<a name="graphs"></a><h3>Graphs and Charts</h3>
<b>Read the descriptions below, and click on the titles for a graphical representation:</b>
<p>
<center><a href="chart13.gif">Competing Deficit Reduction Plans:</a></center>
<P>
"President Clinton has developed two official budgets over the past year.  The first one, issued in January, 1995, was never intended to balance the budget over the next decade.  The second Clinton budget, issued in June 1995, was said to reach a balance in 2005.  However, as this graph shows, the Congressional Budget Office estimates that the President's second budget will never actually balance the budget.  In contrast, the Congressional Balanced Budget Plan of 1995 reaches a balance in 2002, according to the Congressional Budget Office."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart14.gif">GDP in 2002....</a></center>
<p>
"Balancing the budget and cutting taxes over seven years produces $10.8 billion more in Gross Domestic Product.  The red bar below shows the level of Gross Domestic Product, a measure of all the final sales within the United States, that is forecast in the year 2002 if nothing is done to balance the budget or lower taxes.  The blue bar shows that a higher level of GDP can be expected in 2002 with a balanced federal budget and tax cuts."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart5.gif">Additional Consumption Expenditures From A Balanced Budget</a></center>
<p>
"One result of a balanced budget with tax cuts is some $66.2 billion more in consumption expenditures that the American people, not the government, are able to spend on everything from groceries to houses."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart7.gif">Additional Non-Residential Fixed Investment With A Balanced Budget and Tax Cuts</a></center>
<p>
"This graph shows that a balanced budget with tax cuts will allow companies to build more factories and buy more machinery:  $88.2 billion more.  This increased spending represents lasting investments, primarily in the manufacturing sector."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart8.gif">Additional Business Investment in Computers.....</a></center>
<p>
"Another advantage of a balanced budget with tax cuts is that businesses will be able to invest in computers.  This will allow American workers to be more productive and in turn make American companies more competitive."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart12.gif">Additional Investment in Durable Goods....</a></center>
<p>
"A balanced budget with tax cuts means that Americans will be spending $66.2 billion more in consumption.  This graph shows that a large part of that additional spending will be for producers' durable, things like microwaves, air conditioners, and other appliances.  In other words, a balanced budget with tax cuts will allow Americans to invest in lasting, household goods."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart11.gif">Additional Purchases of New Automobiles....</a></center>
<p>
"A balanced budget with tax cuts means that Americans will be able to purchase about $10 billion worth of new automobiles over the next seven years.  That means that about 600,000 new automobiles will be built and purchased."
<hr><P>
<center><a href="chart9.gif">Conventional Mortgage Rates.....</a></center>
<p>
"A balanced budget with tax cuts could lower interest rates.  Over the next seven years a balanced budget with tax cuts might lower rates 0.5% below what they are expected to be without a balanced budget.  This 0.5% decrease means that a home borrower of $100,000 would save about $10,000 over a thirty-year mortgage."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart4.gif">Additional Housing Starts.....</a></center>
<p>
"Lower mortgage interest rates means that more people will be able to afford a house.  A balanced budget with tax cuts could lead to the construction of nearly 104,000 new homes over the next seven years.  This means not only new homes but also more good-paying construction jobs."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart10.gif">Inflation.....</a></center>
<p>
"Perhaps most importantly, a balanced budget with tax cuts would likely lower the rate of inflation by almost a full percentage point.  Thus, prices will not rise as quickly.  This is most beneficial to senior citizens and younger people who are living on a fixed income."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart_3.gif">$500-Per-Child Tax Credit Worksheet</a></center>
<p>
"The Congressional Balanced Budget Plan of 1995 includes a $500 per child tax credit.  This tax credit will help more than 28 million American families raising 51 million children.  To most families $500 would help pay one months mortgage payment or rent."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart2.gif">$500-Per-Child Tax Credit Benefits Middle Class Most</a></center> 
<p>
"Contrary to what most people have been saying, the $500 per child tax credit benefits mostly middle and lower class families.  In fact, 96 percent goes to families making below $100,000 per year."
<hr><p>
<center><a href="chart1.gif">Income Taxes</a></center>
<p>
"This graph shows that the $500 per-child tax credit benefits those at lower incomes more than the wealthy.  In fact, about 3.5 million families would have their entire income tax burden eliminated by the $500 per-child tax credit."
<hr><p><P>
