Public Accountability,&quot; <I>NASSP Bulletin</I>, March, 1982,
p. 69.

<p>

<li>Irving Kristol,  &quot;Social Reform:  Gains and Losses,&quot;
<I>Neoconservatism:  The Autobiography of an Idea</I>, New York:
The Free Press, 1995, p. 200.

<p>

<li>William Raspberry, &quot;Why We're Losing Sight of the Common
Good,&quot; <I>The Washington Post</I>, Feb. 23, 1996. 

<p>

<li>Luntz Weber Research and Strategic Services, &quot;Lessons from
California:  Exit Poll Results of Proposition 174 and a Look at
the Future of School Choice Initiatives,&quot; Nov. 1993, Washington
D.C., pp. 15-16.

<p>

<li><I>Mueller et al. v. Allen et al</I>.  463 U.S. 388 (1983).

<p>

<li>Alan G. Lance, Attorney General, letter to Pete T. Cenarrusa,
Secretary of State, July 24, 1995.

<p>

<li>National Center for Education Statistics, &quot;Schools and
Staffing Survey, 1993-94,&quot;  U.S. Department of Education,
Office of Educational Research and Improvement.

<p>

<li>For further explanation of the two-tiered approach, see William
R. Mattox, Jr., &quot;The One-House Schoolroom:  The Extraordinary
Influence of Family Life on Student Learning,&quot; <i>Family Policy,</i> 
Family Research Council, September, 1995.

<p>

<li>Charles L. Glenn, <I>Choice of Schools in Six Nations</I>, Washington,
D.C.:  U.S. Department of Education, Office of Educational Research
and Improvement, 1989, p. iii. 

<p></ol></font>

