<html>

<title>Gary Bauer's April, 1996 Letter</title>

<body>

<center><h2>A Message From Gary L. Bauer</h2></center>

<p><hr width=75% height=2><p>

April 15, 1996

<p><center>

<i>

&quot;We are troubled on every side, yet not distressed;<br>
we are perplexed, but not in despair;<br>
Persecuted, but not forsaken; cast down, but not destroyed.&quot;

<p>

-2 Corinthians 4: 8-9

</i>

</center><p>

Dear Friend:

<p>

I write to you this month on a subject that weighs heavily on
my heart.  That subject is the persecution of believers around
the world, including here in the United States.  As I've learned
more about the nature and extent of this persecution, it has become
increasingly clear to me that as Christians, we must do more for
our suffering brothers and sisters both here and abroad.  From
China to Saudi Arabia to Sudan, one's profession of faith in Jesus
Christ is becoming an ever more dangerous act in the eyes of the
state.  It is time for men and women of faith to speak up!

<p>

Michael Horowitz is one man who has courageously raised his voice
on this issue.  Mike and I go back many years, to the days when
we both served in the Reagan administration.  My primary responsibilities
were education and the family.  Mike's were economic and regulatory
matters in the Office of Management and Budget.  We worked together
on several issues, and I observed the character of this man up
close.  For that reason, it didn't surprise me at all last summer
when Mike Horowitz, who is Jewish, wrote a heart-rending article
on anti-Christian persecution for <I>The Wall Street Journal.</I>

<p>

Mike was appalled by the harassment, physical abuse and
even death being routinely inflicted on Christians overseas.
But he was even more appalled by the continued refusal of our
government to focus on and do anything about this persecution.
And I have been deeply disappointed by the timidity and silence
that unfortunately have reigned among so many Christians in America,
who, myself included, needed to hear the eloquence of Mike Horowitz
to be shaken with the conviction that we must act.

<p>

This past January, I attended a meeting of evangelical leaders
in Washington, DC that Mike cosponsored with Freedom House.  Freedom
House is a widely respected human rights organization, founded
at the outbreak of World War II.  The information they shared
regarding systematic persecution of Christians was overwhelming:

<p><ul>

<li>Incidents of intimidation, arrest, and torture are growing
under various regimes around the world.  The worst offenders are 
Islamic fundamentalist governments and communist regimes. Millions 
of Christians worldwide are routinely subjected to this persecution, 
most of which goes unreported in the United States.

<p>

<li>In Sudan, 1.5 million people have died as a result of the Islamic
north's <i>jihad</i>, or &quot;holy war,&quot; against the largely 
Christian south.[1] The war has displaced another 5 million. Children 
of Christian parents are being conscripted for service in the
Islamic government army.  One mother, of boys eight and nine,
was imprisoned and savagely beaten when she went to retrieve them 
from a <i>mujahadeen</i> training camp.[2] She was pregnant at the 
time. Thousands of children of Christian parents, as young as six, 
have been taken and sold as slaves in Sudan, Libya and elsewhere.[3]

<p>

<li>Three of the most prominent evangelical leaders in Iran were
abducted and murdered in 1994.  The law there effectively prohibits
Christians from attending any kind of religious service, and those 
who dare to evangelize have been arrested, brutally tortured, and 
forced to renounce their faith.[4]

<p>

<li>Christians who flee Iran through Turkey are forced by the American
Embassy there to undergo interviews by Turkish security police who are
sympathetic toward Iran's laws against &quot;blasphemy.&quot;  Many of 
these refugees fail these interviews and face forcible return to Iran. 
American Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) field offices 
commonly treat refugees the same way.[5] In other words, the only things 
we are &quot;exporting&quot; to Iran are Christians!

<p>

<li>The government of Egypt, which has received billions of dollars
in U.S. assistance (our tax money!), has attempted to appease 
domestic Islamic fundamentalists by imprisoning and torturing Christian 
converts and evangelists.

<p>

<li>In China, persecution of the country's estimated 30 million
Christians is a matter of official public policy.  Catholics in the 
People's Republic are permitted to join only the official state church, 
whose bishops are appointed by Beijing and not by the pope. If they 
refuse to &quot;register,&quot; they are routinely imprisoned and
tortured or, in the classic communist style, &quot;re-educated
through labor&quot; -- the official euphemism for doing hard time in 
the labor camps.

</ul><p>

Recently, FRC's chief of government relations, Marty Dannenfelser,
testified before a House International Relations subcommittee
on this plague of persecution.  He made it clear that our government
has not done enough to highlight and to halt these disgraceful
abuses.  We reject the idea that these problems will go away through
quiet diplomacy, or that abuses will only increase if our government
openly criticizes the perpetrators.  History shows that speaking
out is the only way to deter tyrants.

<p>

Our own government must cease its tolerance of the mistreatment
of religious minorities around the world.  Saudi Arabia is a prime
example.  Recently the Saudis pressured the United States about
&quot;objectionable&quot; activities by American nationals stationed
there.  One complaint involved the operation of a U.S.-sponsored
nightclub frequented by American servicemen.  Our government dug
in its heels and refused to bow to Saudi requests to close it.
At the same time, the Saudis demanded that we stop holding Sunday
worship services at our embassy in Riyadh -- that is, on U.S. soil!
To this, the Clinton Administration buckled under.

<p>

I mentioned at the beginning of this letter that the United States
is also troubled by anti-Christian persecution.  The major difference,
of course, is that the examples I am about to cite are not sponsored
or tolerated by our government.  Nevertheless, their impact on
the religious liberties we hold so dear can be just as devastating.
In the past few years, the United States has experienced a wave
of violent attacks on Christian churches.  According to an investigative
report compiled by <I>USA Today</I>, some 25 black churches, primarily
in the South, have been the targets of arson.  The pace of these
attacks is clearly accelerating.

<p>

The wave seems to have begun on April 4, 1993, the 25th anniversary
of the assassination of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. 
Twelve churches were burned last year, and so far this year at
least seven more have been torched.  In roughly two thirds of
these incidents, no arrests have been made.  This month, of course,
brings another anniversary of Dr. King's death, and many fear
that the attacks on churches will worsen.  Again, the only way
to prevent this tragedy from happening is for each of us to speak
out against these crimes and for the government to bring the 
perpetrators to justice.

<p>

In February, FRC joined with several evangelical, Jewish, Catholic
and civil rights groups in calling for congressional hearings
into these incidents.  The Federal Bureau of Investigation has
also begun to investigate them, but the added visibility of Congressional
hearings can serve a number of useful purposes.  After our call
for hearings, the Congressional Family Caucus, whose roster includes
several dozen freshman members of Congress, also issued a plea
for hearings.  As I'm writing this, FRC has received assurances
from House Judiciary Committee staff that in-depth hearings will
occur later this spring.

<p>

FRC is also calling upon the Clinton administration to speak
out forcefully on these events.  Attorney General Janet Reno shoulders
a special responsibility to ensure that potential arsonists know
that the full weight of federal law enforcement will be brought
to bear to end these attacks.  We have publicly urged her to show
the same zeal in pursuing the perpetrators of these incidents
as she has shown in pursuing her theories of conspiracy among
peaceful protestors outside abortion clinics!

<p>

It's too early to know for certain, but these attacks on churches
are most likely motivated by both religious <b>and</b> racial
bigotry.  Anti-Christian bigotry is the American &quot;exception&quot; 
-- the only acceptable form of intolerance in modern America.  Just 
consider how muffled the response was to the invasion of St. Patrick's
Cathedral in New York by members of the homosexual group Act-Up.
The Montrose Baptist Church, in suburban Washington, DC, has
also been the target of two suspicious fires in recent years.
It is probably no coincidence that the church was heavily involved
on the pro-life side of Maryland's recent abortion referendum.

<p>

Racial prejudice is obviously at work, too.  The damage it wreaks
on America's social fabric is astonishing.  It makes me wonder
if Americans will ever judge one another by the content of our
character, and not the color of our skin.  Can this hatred that
affronts the gospel of Christ continue to divide our house and
drag this nation down?  Our greatest hope is for spiritual revival
to again sweep our land and to bring about healing through reconciliation
within families and between races.  Then and only then will we
know our country is well on the road to recovery.

<p>

The seeds of ethnic hatred should find no fertile soil in this
land we love. That is why I included the following statement
in the Compact with Our Fellow Americans that appears in my new
book, <I>Our Hopes, Our Dreams</I>:

<p><blockquote>

<i>

In our work and community life, we promise to elevate a public
ethic of individual merit, regardless of ethnic or national origin, 
or political or religious belief. We will not tolerate the expression, 
public or private, of bigotry on any such basis.  We will judge 
all persons we meet by the content of their character, not the color 
of their skin.

</i>

</blockquote><p>

As this statement suggests, the task of combating religious and
racial hatred is not, first of all, the task of government.  It
is every citizen's task, a battle within the heart that, won there,
cannot be lost in the public square.

<p>

In closing, let me ask that you take up your pen right away and
urge your representatives in Congress to act decisively on these
twin issues.  With a united America behind them, they will be
empowered to act boldly.  In the meantime, let us heed the words
of the apostle Paul and cast off all distress and despair.  Where
we have Christ, we have hope.

<p>

We at FRC feel greatly blessed to be in the heart of our nation's
capital, with the daily chance to address our political leaders
on these vital concerns.  Your friendship and financial support
are part of that blessing, and you have my deepest thanks for
remembering us.  If your circumstances permit, your gift to us
this month will mean so much to our campaign on behalf of family,
faith, and freedom.  Your continued involvement and support are
essential to our success.

<p>

Sincerely,

<p><br>

Gary L. Bauer<br>
President

<p>

P.S. It's always difficult to end a letter like this with a
little house-keeping, but the enclosures this month require some
explanation.  As you know, FRC communicates with you on a regular
basis. You most likely receive both my monthly letter and <I>Washington
Watch,</I> and perhaps other mailings as well. Our goal
is to ensure that every item we send you is useful to your family.
At the same time, we are keenly aware of our responsibility to
exercise stewardship over the resources you entrust to us.  If
you are receiving any mail from FRC that is not meeting your needs,
this is your chance to let us know.  We look forward to continuing
to send you the timeliest pro-family reports available today.

<p>

Please return the enclosed card at your earliest opportunity and note, 
that while we do hope you will respond, <b>no financial gift is 
necessary</b>. Your reply will aid us in serving you -- and many more 
families besides -- to the best of our ability. God bless you.

<p><hr><p>

<font size=-1><ol>

<p>

<li>Letter from Darren A. Jones, Christian Solidarity International, 
to Melissa McClard, Family Research Council, March 14, 1995, p. 1.

<p>

<li>"Forcible Conscription of Children in Sudan," Press Release, 
Christian Solidarity International, February 12, 1996 (Washington, 
D.C.).

<p>

<li>Michael Horowitz, "New Intolerance Between Crescent and Cross," 
<i>The Wall Street Journal</i>, July 5, 1995.

<p>

<li>Ibid.

<p>

<li>Ibid.

</ol></font>

<p><hr width=60%><p>

