<html>
<title> Tax Limitation Amendment</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<br>
<center>
<h2><i>Tax Limitation</i></h2> <br>		             
</center>

Although April 15th is always an important day in the Unites States, this year, this day will earmark a hopeful turn of events.  The Tax Limitation Amendment, one of the first reform acts of the 104th Congress, will go to the House floor on April 15th.  Sponsored by over 166 Representatives, this amendment would require Congress to have a two-thirds majority vote in each house to approve tax-rate increases. <p> 

Senator Kyl (R-AZ) is the driving force behind the amendment for the Senate.  Senator Kyl has proposed that if this bill passes it would need ratification by 38 states in order to become the 28th amendment to the U.S. Constitution. <p>

One of the key factors to passing this bill would not only make it harder for Congress to raise taxes, but would force lawmakers to prioritize government spending.  The bill was written to encourage the elimination of lower priority programs to pay for new proposals as opposed to seeking finances through raised taxes. <p>

Recent surveys and studies have shown that the majority of American voters support the Tax Limitation Amendment.  The bill has also received tremendous backing from many high profile organizations, such as the American Conservative Union, the Christian Coalition, Citizens Against Government Waste, Family Research Council, and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. <p>

Below is a layout of the proposed bill and some of the key reasons why it would stabilize tax laws: <p>

 <p> <br> <br> <br> 
					
					<center>April 15 Floor Vote </center> <p>

Section 1.<p>
	Any bill to increase taxes by increasing the rate or base of any tax may pass only by a two-thirds majority of the whole number of each House of Congress. <p>

Section 2.<p>
	Waiver during periods of declared war or imminent and serious threat to national security declared by a joint resolution.  Any provision which passed subject to the waiver shall last no more than 2 years. <p>

Section 3.<p>
	All votes will be roll call votes. <p>

<p> <br>  <br> 

				 <center>	Talking Points </center> <p>
<ul>
<li>The Kemp Commission on Tax Reform endorsed a 2/3rds super-majority requirement for tax increases. It is an essential part of any tax reform.<p>

<li> One-third of all Americans live in a state with tax limitation in their constitutions: Arizona, Arkansas, California, Colorado, Delaware, Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi, Oklahoma, and South Dakota.  Other states are pursuing similar measures. <p>

<li> In the last decade, taxes in non-super-majority states went up 104%.  In super-majority requirement states, tax revenues went up only 87%. <p>

<li> In the last decade, spending in non-super-majority states went up 102%.  In states with the super-majority protection, spending increased only 95%. <p>

<li> It must be more difficult for future Congresses to raise taxes. Because federal benefits tend to be targeted at specific groups, special interest groups consistently come together to effectively lobby for more spending.  Taxes, on the other hand are spread among many millions of people who would find it difficult to band together as an interest group. The built-in pressure in a democracy is toward more spending.  The super-majority provision successfully balances the pressure. <p>

<li> Four of the last five major tax increases were passed with less than a two-thirds super-majority.  Those taxes added an additional $666 billion to the tax bill for the American taxpayer. <p>

<li> On Day One of the 104th Congress, the House voted 279-152 for a super-majority requirement to raise income taxes -- 11 votes shy of two-thirds.  This important protection, though, only applies during the 104th Congress, and only to the House. <p>
</ul> <p>
<p> <br> <br>


Official Supporters for the Tax Limitation Amendment: <p>
<p> <br>
<a href="/conservative/"> American Conservative Union </a> <br>
<a  href="/atr/1.html">  Americans for Tax Reform </a> <br>
<a href="/govt-waste/"> Citizens Against Government Waste </a> <br>
<a href="/townhall/FRC"> Family Research Council </a> <br>
<a href="/sbsc/"> Small Business Survival Committee </a> <br>
<a href="http://www.cais.net/chamber/"> U.S. Chamber of Commerse </a> <br>
<a href="http://www.cc.org">  Christian Coalition </a> <br>
<!-- <a href="http://www.cse.org"> Citizens for a Sound Economy </a> <br> -->
<a href="http://www.nawga-ifda.org"> National -American Wholesale Grocers'  Association </a> <br>
<a href="http://www.nam.org"> National Association of Manufacturers </a> <br>
<a href="http://www.senate.gov/senator/kyl.html"> Senator John Kyl  </a> <br>
<a href="http://www.house.gov/barton/welcome.html">Congressman Joe Barton </a> <br>
<br><br><p>
<CENTER><A HREF="/townhall/tbut.map">
<IMG SRC="/townhall/tbutt2.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER>
