<HEAD>

<TITLE>In Search of the New Majority - PFF</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<blockquote><blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<br><br>
<h2>In Search of the New Majority</h2>
</B>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Remarks by Vin Weber, Frank Luntz and Andrew Kohut</B><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<font size="-1">
<a href="#introduction">Introduction</a><br>
<a href="#has">Has There Been a Political Revolution</a><br>
<a href="#who">Who is the New Majority</a><br>
<a href="#where">Where is American Public Opinion Headed</a><br>
</font size>
<p>
<I>The following remarks were delivered at &quot;The New Majority:  Democratic Governance in a Revolutionary Age&quot; conference, hosted by The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation on January 22, 1996.  The conference explored the possibility of political realignment and asked:  Is there a &quot;new majority&quot; taking shape in America and other western-style democracies?  Who is part of the new majority, what are its beliefs - and how is it related to the transition from an industrial to an information-age economy?  Which (if either) American political party is best positioned to represent it?  And, what impact will it have on the 1996 presidential election?
<p>
<a name="introduction"></a>
</I><CENTER><B>Introduction
by Jeffrey A. Eisenach<B><SUP>*</SUP> 
</B></B></CENTER>
<p>
Many people infer that the title, The New Majority, has something to do with the recent events in the United States Congress, the development of a new majority, a Republican majority, in the House and in the Senate.  While that event in November 1994 certainly is part of the phenomenon we are describing, the new majority that we are talking about here today is in fact a much larger and broader phenomenon.  One of the underlying premises of the work that we do at The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation is the notion that we are in a time of Big Change, the transition from an Industrial Age to an Information Age, and a series of very profound cultural, economic, political and social changes that accompany that.  On the political side, that clearly will involve the creation of new coalitions, not only in politics, not only in America, but around the world.  
<p>
The new majority that we are talking about here today is an Information Age majority.  It is not yet clear which political party will represent that new majority, whether it will be called Republican, Democratic or by some new name.  Indeed, the politics of 1995 as they have played out have not, in my view, and in the view of many of those you will hear today, represented the politics of the new debate.  
<p>
In many ways, the Republican agenda as it's taken shape and been explained on Capitol Hill more resembles the fiscal conservatism of Herbert Hoover than the vision of Newt Gingrich.  By the same token, the Democratic minority on Capitol Hill appears to much better represent the Welfare State, Great Society message of Lyndon Johnson than the visionary speeches of President Clinton.  
<p>
We are in a time of Big Change.  It is a time of opportunity.  It is a time of danger.  Today we discuss what that means in terms of the shape of American politics, its implications for 1996, and its implications beyond.  
<a name="has"></a>
<p><CENTER><B>Has there Been a Political Revolution?
by Vin Weber<B><SUP>*</SUP> 
</B></B></CENTER>
<p>
All the time I encounter political associates who argue that if such and such a thing happens, the Republican revolution will be over.  If we nominate the wrong presidential candidate or if Bill Clinton gets re-elected or if we don't get the right conclusion to the budget agreement, then the revolution will be over.  
<p>
I'm here to argue that the revolution <I>is</I> over, that we want the revolution to be over, and that we ought to think of the revolution as being over.  To think of an ongoing revolution is a mistake.
<p>
Revolutions are actions that overturn an existing order. Successful revolutions end quickly and then the revolutionaries get on with the business of rebuilding society consistent with the principles that drove the revolution.  I think it is a political mistake for Republicans to continue to talk about revolution.  It may stir the faithful, but it scares the average voter.  And more importantly, I think it misinterprets and incorrectly analyzes what the state of the country politically is and where we are.  Simply put: the revolution is over, we've won, and it's time to think more seriously about rebuilding society consistent with the principles that brought the revolution to power.
<p>
The first question people might ask is have we really won?  After all, Bill Clinton is still President, much of the Contract With America, perhaps most of it, will not become law until there's a change in the presidency, and there's ample reason to believe that we haven't changed the way the country is governed. I think that's all true. Yet, we have experienced a political revolution in the form of a major intellectual and ideological realignment.
<p>
A fundamental change in the way the voters perceive government, it's usefulness, it's ability to interact successfully with them, it's relationship to individual people and communities:  it is in this sense that I would argue that we had a successful revolution and a successful realignment, and we are now going about the business of rebuilding society.  
<p>
The last genuine realignment was in the 1930's, culminating about three decades of political turmoil in the country featuring Progressives and Populists and Bull Moosers and all sorts of other insurgents within the existing two-party order.  In 1933, Eleanor Roosevelt said &quot;One has a feeling of going it blindly because we are in a tremendous stream and none of us knows where we are going to land.&quot;  At the beginning of the great revolution that became known as the New Deal, with a huge mandate from the voters and being the most ideologically oriented person in the Administration, certainly much more so than her husband the President, Eleanor Roosevelt still had this sense that she was in a dark room and didn't really know where to go.  They were making up the New Deal as they went along.  For us to look back today, 60 years later, we could fall into the trap of thinking that this was all very carefully planned from the outset, the building of what we now call the Liberal Welfare State.  
<p>
It's important for us to understand that this wasn't the case.  You found that they made up quite a bit as they went along. Mrs. Roosevelt reflected most of the thinking of the New Deal: lots of optimism and lots of ideas, but not a clear plan in any sense.  They did, however, have a model that made a lot of sense to them and surprisingly that model really came from corporate America.  Some writers have argued only half facetiously that the real father of the New Deal was not Franklin Roosevelt but Henry Ford. Alvin and Heidi Toffler have written about the impact of what Henry Ford and other captains of industry did around the turn of the century in providing a model for the New Dealers when they went into government. Business was in the process of reorganizing and regimenting America, forcing massive population movements from the country into the city, organizing business along the factory model with hierarchically structured corporate organizations. Standardization was the key word.
<p>
The New Deal planners had this model of corporate America that seemed to be the wave of the future. Top down, hierarchical command and control structures, standardization, regimentation organization: That was how successful enterprises were organized.  It followed that government should be organized in the same way. It helped a great deal that President Roosevelt had the twin disasters of the Depression and World War Two to focus the country's attention, but nonetheless part of the process had been going on for some time.  In short, it just made sense to the American people.  By the end of Roosevelt's first term, people really had a new conception of how government should interact with people, and it was consistent with the other changes that they saw taking place around them.
<p>
Their conception of the proper role of government dominated our politics until 1980. It's imperative to recognize that it was not simply one party - although the Democrats benefited proportionally from it - but both parties basically accepted the same premise about how government should approach problem solving. The notion that the country swung back to the Republicans when Eisenhower was elected really is a misreading if you think about what happened.  Eisenhower, and Nixon as well, simply validated the New Deal, liberal welfare state approach to problem solving by embracing it.  Eisenhower was quite specific in office about saying he did not want to go back and repeal the New Deal.  He wanted to invent &quot;modern Republicanism.&quot;  Nixon, when he was in office, established the EPA, OSHA and imposed price controls.  In both cases, they accepted what had become the conventionalism since the successful Roosevelt revolution, which was that Federal Government activity, centrally structured, hierarchically organized, standardized in approach, was the way in which government operated to solve problems. 
<p>
The first President really not to be a part of that consensus was Ronald Reagan.  It's not that he was successful in rolling it back, but he really did not accept those premises and did not try in any way to expand the liberal welfare state as every President, Republican and Democrat alike, had done from Roosevelt up unto Reagan.  	
<p>

Now, to restate my basic point: I believe that a similar realignment in thinking has occurred.  Just as the realignment of our country's thinking that took place in the 1930's had gestated for 30 years or so with the Progressives and the Populists, there's been a long period of gestation and rejection of New Deal, Great Society liberalism today. It began with Barry Goldwater, who challenged the Republican Party's acceptance of those principles, and culminated in Ronald Reagan, who ran a campaign basically against the Welfare State.  
<p>
What confirmed the realignement was not so much the 1994 elections, but the health care debate earlier that year.  After the Clinton health care plan was interred in September of 1994 by <I>The Washington Post</I>, <I>The New York Times</I> and others, it was interesting to watch the analysis from all of the smarter-than-thou people around Washington - people in the media, people in the think tanks, people in politics - all explaining that, of course the Clinton health care plan was doomed from the start because&#133;fill in the blank.  Either because the President put his wife in charge of it, or because Ira Magaziner had never succeeded in anything, and 15 other reasons why.  Yet the amazing thing about the failure of Clinton's health care plan was that it failed.
<p>
It was the first time that a Democrat President, carrying a substantial Congressional majority, running a campaign based on a promise of a tangible benefit to a middle class constituency, addressing a real problem, failed to deliver.  He couldn't deliver not so much because he simply couldn't control or discipline his Congress, but because public support for it collapsed.  Support for Clinton's plan went from 60 percent plus when he initiated it to about 30 percent when it died.  It went from being the issue that many Democrats thought was going to be their key issue in preventing normal mid-term election losses, to the issue that by the last two or three weeks of the campaign Republican strategists were telling their challengers to use against the Democratic incumbent as symbolizing everything that they wanted to be against.  That's a remarkable transformation.
<p>
The more people learned about Clinton's plan, the less they liked it. They didn't like it because it was bureaucratic and costly and centralized and all those things.  So what's new?  Name me a New Deal Great Society program that wasn't attacked by Republican opponents as being bureaucratic, costly and centralized.  The difference is this time it worked.
<p>
The ratification of this revolution in people's thinking is the fact that President Clinton appears to have accepted it.  He has not reinitiated a new health care proposal, nor does Clinton have any other major new Federal initiatives that he's putting before the Congress.  In his 1996 State of the Union message, the President said &quot;the era of big government is over.&quot;  He talked a good deal about foreign policy success, bragged about the health of the economy, threw up a few liberal slogans on Medicare and Medicaid, but we saw no stirring defense of the Department of Commerce, no call for establishing any new Federal agencies.
<p>
That the President is already acting substantially within the parameters of the new context of American politics validates my argument that the revolution has succeeded.  In this regard, Clinton is less today Franklin Roosevelt or his hero, John Kennedy, than he is the Eisenhower of our new realignment, the first Democratic President to essentially govern within the constraints of this newly realigned country, with in the new thinking about the appropriate role for government.
<p>
The challenge, then, is not necessarily one of &quot;keeping the revolution alive,&quot; but to move ahead as quickly and wisely as we can with the rebuilding of society in the wake of the revolution.  That's hard work because although the public has largely rejected New Deal, Great Society, welfare state liberalism or whatever words you want to add to my description of it, there really is no evidence that they want to go back to a pre-New Deal conception of government.
<p>
Yet there is a great risk for Republicans to conclude this realignment is simply a dismantlingly of government. After all, in the 1992 election not too long ago, Democrats won largely on the issue of insufficient government activism. They argued that President Bush had no agenda domestically or economically, and people wanted more activism from their government.  The third party candidate, Perot, did not talk about diminishing or shrinking government, he talked about getting under the hood and fixing government.
<p>
Some pundits think the tension between an electorate seemingly wanting an activist government in 1992 and one wanting to greatly reduce the size of government in 1994 shows and immature and spoiled public. Supposedly voters want lower taxes and less government while demanding solutions to all the social problems like health care and the environment.  Many pundits say that voters can't have it both ways and are going to have to be forced to make a choice.
<p>
I don't think that's the case.  The public is sending a strong, strong signal to politicians that they want a different way of approaching problems, and they're going to be ready to turn politicians out until they find those people or parties that will devise a new solution, a new way of activism.  I don't have all the answers.  I think the outlines are beginning to come into shape somehow, probably more if you look at governors and mayors than at the federal level. Although some people like John Ashcroft and Dan Coats in the United States Senate are already talking very seriously about how to forge a new domestic policy, bringing in non-governmental organizations, churches and others more actively into the solution of some of our social problems.  Certainly at the level of governors and mayors, you find people like Steve Goldsmith in Indianapolis experimenting with new concepts, utilizing privatization, trying to grab a hold of community and tap non-governmental sources to solve problems.
<p>
There is, just as at the beginning of the New Deal, something to be invented today. We are only beginning to see its outlines.  It'll be very clear to people when they look back on it 20 or 30 years from now, but our challenge is to make sure that we get beyond the dismantling of the state and actually think seriously about how we build a conservative opportunity society, something that replaces the liberal welfare state. The party or people that do that will be the majority for another 40 years.  	
<p>
<a name="who"></a>
<CENTER><B>Who Is the New Majority?
by Frank Luntz<B><SUP>*</SUP> </B></B></CENTER>
<p> 
It is not an election itself that causes political revolutions.  If you ask Americans today whether they believe that there's been a change since 1994, three out of four would say not.  So if there's been a revolution, you better wake up the American people.  They don't see it.  Even when the Federal government was closed, 88 percent of Americans said it did not affect them at all.
<p>
Yet there is a new majority taking shape in the electorate.  The best way to understand a majority is to understand what the average American is like. 
<p>
She - because men smoke too much, drink too much, work too hard and die too young - is Jennifer Smith.  She's 32.7 years old.  She's white. She comes from European ancestry.  She lives in a mortgaged suburban home that has three bedrooms and a pet and is heated by natural gas.  She likes living there, but she is thinking about moving to something larger.  Jennifer is a happily married mother at least for now.  The strange thing about survey research is that I know she will become unhappy in about three or four years but I don't have the heart to tell her.  She watches about four hours of TV a day between work and raising a family.  She has a high school diploma, perhaps a little bit of college but she does someday hope to get that college degree.  She works in a service job but has higher aspiration.
<p>
Like her husband, John, Jennifer has her own car, and she drives to work alone each day.  There's a direct correlation, by the way, between those that car pool and registration of Democrats and Liberals. So whenever you see a car pool lane, you know that the people driving it are most likely to be Democrats.  Now the difference between her and her husband is that when they both reach a yellow light, she will stop and he will drive right through.  She attends church once a week, although she occasionally misses a week here and there.  She prays quietly to herself almost once a day, and she strongly believes in God.  Even though she feels the American dream is somewhat alive, Jennifer thinks the nation is in serious trouble and that some country other than America will be the number one economic superpower by the year 2020.
<p>
Emotionally, Jennifer is frustrated and anxious, particularly about crime and the economy, but she is less concerned than her husband.  She believes that the federal deficit is spinning out of control, and she thinks that her elected officials waste 48 cents out of every dollar.  She votes only once every four years.  She hates partisan politics and has very little confidence in the Federal government.  She does not trust politicians, and she's skeptical of the media, of lawyers and of the legal system - although she did follow the O. J. Simpson trial virtually every day.  She doesn't know if the two party system is salvageable, nor does she really care.  However, she does believe that her local community is headed in the right direction and she is somewhat optimistic that her own personal situation will improve.  She and her husband are charitable people; they do give more than one percent of their income to charity. They want to help those that are less fortunate, but they simply don't want their tax dollars going to Welfare.  They don't want the charity to come from Washington, to come from a bureaucracy. She's a patient person, but her patience is running out.
<p>
In short, Jennifer Smith believes in our government in abstract principles - democracy and capitalism for example - but she has little confidence in institutions - the Presidency, the Congress or the courts.  She believes in herself, but she wonders whether society will bring her down.  Jennifer and her 263 million compatriots see the American dream slipping out of their grasp and even farther out of the reach of her children.  She doesn't believe the American dream is dead - in fact, only 15 percent of Americans do - but she thinks it's very sick.  
<p>
(The problem that I have in saying that the new majority has won, that the new majority exists today and that it's in the Republican Party, is that the Republican Party has not successfully appealed to Jennifer Smith.)
<p>
That's a demographic look at the average American.  Now I want to give you an attitudinal look, and I want to start with what the new majority rejects because from a public opinion standpoint it is easier to tell you what they are against than to tell you what they are for.  
<p>
They reject the Federal welfare system above all else.  When you talk to a so-called member of the new majority, if you want to see the emotion and the passion, it doesn't come from a balanced budget.  It doesn't come even from crime.  What makes them really spitting angry - where they start to use four letter words -is the welfare system, how destructive it is, how unfair it is, how vicious it is, and how they want to eliminate it. If there's one great opportunity that Republicans have in 1996, it's to tie the welfare system around President Clinton's neck and sink him with it.  It's like lead boots that the so-called wise guys used to use on informants when they would throw them off some beach down south of Miami.  The welfare system is that around President Clinton's neck.  
<p>
What next makes members of the new majority most angry is the public school system, with increasing Federal control, mediocrity and the fact that there seems to be more bureaucracy to it.  They're angry at a Federal tax code that is anti-work, anti-investments, anti-savings and, when you talk to middle class, anti-success.  They reject the expense of Federal bureaucracy.  It seems to serve its own interest, and what freaked them out is something that came out of a David Letterman routine when he made the comment: &quot;If 80 percent of our Federal workers are non-essential, doesn't that send us a message?&quot; The one thing that I don't understand is why we Republicans did not draw the line back in December and say if they're not essential, why are they here, and if they're not working, why are we paying them? How many of you, if you don't come to work because there's a furlough, if you're not producing day after day and you're out of work for two weeks, three weeks, how many of your bosses or you yourself will get paid?  What are we doing paying people not to work?  It's insanity, and a new majority does not understand that.
<p>
The new majority rejects Federal regulatory-structure red tape.  They do not understand why it takes them so long to fill out forms, why it seems like the government is against them, why a small business can be shut down by OSHA if their toilet paper is one-quarter of an inch too high or too low.  They reject the legal system that has become the most expensive in the world and the most embarrassing at home.  They reject the anti-family mind set that permeates almost all of Washington's social, tax and welfare policies. They reject a government that can't even keep them safe. They reject the Washington ethic that encourages dependency and victimization:  Everyone in America seems to be a victim; It wasn't those poor Mendez brothers fault that they went in and gunned down their parents; They actually went out and reloaded so they could shoot again;  It wasn't their fault; It was society's fault, society to blame.  And, they reject the $5 trillion federal debt that is eroding America's ability to save and invest.
<p>
If there is a new majority, than current politicians, if they wish to succeed, must find a way to communicate to these people, to address their concerns, and not to play in this rhetorical game that we've been in right now. The Republican party is losing this budget debate, and if you think otherwise, then I don't know what TV shows you're watching.  Every day, from Leon Panetta to Donna Shalala, from Robert Reich to George Stephanopolis, they talk about values in the Clinton Administration.  They talk about principles.  They talk about being pro-family, pro-community, and even the President talks about spirituality.  What do Republicans do?  They talk about numbers, and fight over the nuts and bolts.  Any party that wants to lead the new majority cannot do that.  You cannot communicate in trillions and billions when the new majority understands things in hundreds and maybe if it's a mortgage in thousands.
<p>

The central questions the new majority wants answered is:  How many of you believe that you have a better quality of life today than your parents did when they were your age?  And how many of you honestly believe that your children will have a better quality of life than you when they reach your age? 

<p>
Why do so many people answer yes to the first question but not the latter? We have to understand why so many hands went up to the first question and so few hands went up to the second question. If the Republicans are to lead that new majority, as I certainly hope they are, because I don't believe in a third party, then the Republican Party has to communicate to all of you who said yes to the first question but not to the second.
<p>
<a name="where"></a>
<CENTER><B>Where is American Public Opinion Headed?
by Andrew Kohut<B><SUP>*</SUP> 
</B></B></CENTER><p>

If there's a revolution going on, it's not with the American public. We just see no indication that public opinion is in a revolutionary state.  It's certainly changing.  It's more evolving than being in a state of revolution.
<p>
We've been measuring basic political values since 1987.  Each year we do a major national survey and we ask people about how they feel about the government, the national economy and a whole range of social issues.  We see two persistent trends since 1987: less support or more suspicion of political leaders and more cynicism about the way the political system works, and less support for government solutions to national problems.  Consistently, each of our seven or eight measures which attempt to find out how much support there is for government solutions has shown an erosion of support since the mid-1980's.  In 1987, perhaps the average percentage of our samples saying they supported government solutions was at the 70 percent level.  It's slowly eroded to the 60 or 55 level, but it's still there.  
<p>
There is still clear majority support for Federal government solutions to help the poor, to provide a social safety net, to improve the environment, to deal with the problems of education and to deal with a wide variety of problems.  People no longer look to government to solve new problems.  Bureaucracy is in fact a dirty word, and government is seen more than ever as a court of last resort, but it is indeed seen as a court of last resort, and the American public doesn't want to see it go away. 
<p>
Looking at the past 12 months, what we see most clearly is that the public thinks that the new Republican majority on the Hill is cutting government too fast and too far.  They want welfare reform and they want government reform.  They want government changed, but they don't want to see it go away.  Whether they're correct in their perception, they think that the Republicans are going to do away with government to too great an extent.
<p>

I think the most important thing to recognize about American public opinion besides this discontent with the way government works, but still not a total disconnection from it altogether, is that we're in a cycle.  There's always been a change in the American public opinion between wanting the government to solve problems and not liking government, and when the emphasis is on the problems, then the American public doesn't pay a lot of attention to how inefficiently the Government works, or the downside to Government activity.  
<p>
The emphasis now is not on the problems.  People aren't up in arms about the problems of the poor.  The environment is a concern, but it's not a top concern.  The issues that are paramount to people aren't the kinds of things that were the case in the late 1960's and early 1970's when government programs really grew.  Therefore, there's much greater attention to the shortcomings of government activity and the discontents that have been mentioned here.  But the public has in no way in my view walked away from government.  It still wants government to do things that can't be done by the private sector or people can't do themselves, and the American public continues to feel that if all else fails the government should help solve problems - certainly not in the free form way that the American public felt 20 years ago, but nonetheless it's there.
<p>
The most important thing about the new electorate as we have measured it is not so much the left and the right - which are more clearly etched and defined than 10 years ago - but the fact that the middle has become what we describe it in our latest topology as the detached center, because it is so disconnected in terms of ideological thinking and political thinking from the left to the right.  The detachment isn't so much from political belief as it is from political system. The typical American is a high-school educated, middle-aged woman with no connection to the Republican Party or the Democratic Party and has very contradictory views about governance and issues of strong support of the environment, suspicious about higher taxes, worries about government yet a believer in social welfare.  So when I said there's no makings of a revolution in American public opinion, the nature of that political thinking is not revolutionary in the sense except in its detachment from the two political parties.
<p>

</BODY>

