<HEAD>

<TITLE>On the Road to Digital Freedom -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>On the Road to Digital Freedom</h2>
<P>

The Telecommunications Act of  1996 (TCA) represents the most
sweeping reform of telecommunications law in more than 60 years.
 In principle, the new legislation will enable local telephone
companies, long distance companies, cable TV companies, direct
broadcast satellite providers, over-the-air broadcasters, cellular
companies and a host of others to compete against one another
to provide all sorts of communications and information services
in the converging market for digital information and information
technology.  The potential benefits for consumers and for America's
position in the world are beyond calculation.
<P>
The key word in the previous sentence, however, is <I>potential</I>.
 As some commentators have noted, TCA is not, in and of itself,
a deregulatory bill.  Indeed, it mandates over 80 new rulemakings
by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), and delegates
significant authority to state regulators.  If the FCC and the
states use their authority to reduce regulation and encourage
competition, TCA can lead to an efficient, deregulated regime
for the new digital information marketplace and put America on
the road to digital freedom.
<P>
But TCA does not mandate such a result.  In most cases, it gives
the FCC and the states authority to deregulate, but it does not
require that they do so.  For example:
<UL>
<LI>Regulators will oversee the opening of local telephone markets
to competition.  Along the way they will have to address many
difficult technical and economic issues including interconnection,
unbundling, number portability, resale, dialing parity and right-of-way
access.  The nature and pace of the transition is left largely
to regulatory discretion.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Regulators will also implement very broad provisions designed
to change dramatically the current system of &quot;universal service&quot;
subsidies, aiming to target them more to low income households,
collect them in a competitively-neutral fashion and otherwise
reduce them where possible.  
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>The Telecommunications Act of 1996 provides that the FCC &quot;shall
forbear&quot; from regulating where public interest criteria are
met.  How the FCC uses its discretion in implementing this provision
will have a dramatic impact on the pace of deregulation.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>The final days of legislative debate spotlighted the importance
of issues associated with the electromagnetic spectrum.  In coming
months, both the FCC and Congress will consider how current spectrum
management practices should be reformed.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The smoothness and even success of the transition to a competitive
digital marketplace will depend upon how well these issues are
handled.  The consequences for America's future are enormous:
 
<UL>
<LI>Digital information products and services are the most rapidly
growing segment of the world economy, expected to account for
$1 trillion or more in sales by the year 2000.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Technological advances in these areas are the driving force
behind a global transition from an industrial age economy to an
information age economy, literally transforming every aspect of
the world economy, and society itself.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>The social consequences of the transition are profound, and
implementation of TCA will have profound consequences for how
digital technologies are made available to all segments of the
population.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>America's leadership in the world, and ultimately its national
security, are dependent on continuing its leadership role in information
technology. 
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<h3>The Working Group</h3>

<P>
Early last year House Telecom Subcommittee Chairman Jack Fields
asked the Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation for its recommendations
on reforming the Federal Communications Commission.  PFF assembled
a &quot;working group&quot; of top-flight telecom experts and
scholars, many of whom had been senior staffers at the FCC for
several years.  The working group includes:
<UL>
<LI>Dr. Robert Crandall, Brookings Institution;
<LI>Dr. Jeffrey Eisenach, Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation;
<LI>James Gattuso, Esq., Citizens For A Sound Economy;
<LI>Dr. Thomas Hazlett, University of California, Davis;
<LI>Peter W. Huber, Manhattan Institute;
<LI>Dr. George A. Keyworth, Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation;
<LI>Dr. Thomas Lenard, Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation;
<LI>William C. Myers, Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation;
<LI>Peter Pitsch, Esq., Hudson Institute;
<LI>Kenneth Robinson, Esq.;
<LI>Gregory Sidak, Esq., American Enterprise Institute; and
<LI>Adam Thierer, Heritage Foundation.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Last May, the working group produced  a replacement model for
the FCC entitled <I>The Telecom Revolution, An American Opportunity</I>.
 This report outlined an approach for eliminating much of the
current regulatory apparatus and replacing the FCC with a smaller,
leaner oversight agency designed to promote competition.   The
working group report played an important role in educating public
policy leaders and members of the public about the nature of the
transition to a digital environment, and served as the focus of
PFF testimony before both Congress and the FCC; members of the
working group met with leaders in both Houses of Congress on numerous
occasions to brief them on their findings.
<P>
In 1996, Congress has again turned to the working group, with
the chairs of the major oversight committees in both Houses requesting
specific assistance from PFF with respect to issues ranging from
spectrum management, to forebearance, to the structure of the
FCC itself.  FCC Chairman Reed Hundt has also sought PFF's input
and advice.
<P>
<h3>The Project and its Activities</h3>

<P>
PFF's May 1995 report concluded that the pace of technological
change has fundamentally changed the political economy of regulation.
 Innovation has made effective competition possible throughout
the telecom market.  It has also dramatically increased the cost
of regulatory delays and impediments.  The FCC needed to be replaced
by a new, smaller, more focused agency.  
<P>
The Telecommunications Act of 1996 has provided the means and
added impetus for achieving this goal.  The new legislation requires
state and federal regulators to assure that a competitive 14-point
checklist of conditions are met in local exchange markets, before
allowing the regional Bell operating companies to enter the in-region
long distance and equipment manufacturing markets.  The implementation
of the interconnection, network unbundling, and related pricing
issues will be major battlegrounds.  This process is important
to the efficient development of local telecommunications competition
and the expeditious development of additional competition in long
distance and equipment markets.  
<P>
Fashioning universal service reforms will present a stiff political
challenge.  Many interests will press for the expansion of the
definition of universal service.  If these subsidies are not reduced
and targeted, a competitively-neutral system that does not impede
new technology will be difficult to achieve.  The legislation
sets forward specific universal service principles to be observed,
but also gives the FCC considerable latitude to reform the system.
 A convincing record and strategy will be needed to carry out
true reform. 
<P>
To free up needed administrative resources and eliminate counterproductive
regulation, the FCC will need to forbear from regulating in many
areas.  Suitable areas for deregulation will need to be identified
and justified.  At the same time, the FCC will be wrestling with
a raft of other issues ranging from antenna preemption to video
services provided by telephone companies. 
<P>
The legislation has also created an enormous opportunity for the
FCC to spur local telephone competition and the development of
 new wireless services by making more spectrum available through
market mechanisms.  Practical ways of dealing with interference
and other objections to &quot;dezoning&quot; the spectrum will
need to be developed.  Alternative mechanisms of freeing up spectrum,
such as variants of the PCS overlay approach and a more &quot;bottom-up&quot;
approach used in the case of Nextel, will need to be closely examined
and appraised.
<P>
In short, much more detailed work will be needed to effect a smooth
transition to a truly competitive digital information marketplace.
 The updated FCC replacement project will provide a detailed plan
of action building on the new legislation, focusing both on the
implementation of TCA and the need for additional legislation
to further speed the transition.  Given TCA's reliance on devolution
to the states, a telecommunications model for state law and regulation
will also be developed.  Specifically, <I>On The Road to Digital
Freedom</I> will provide important research in six main areas:
<UL>
<LI>The FCC role in creating competitive market conditions in
local telecommunications markets;
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>The FCC role in assuring universal service goals are met;
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Spectrum management reforms that could be undertaken by the
FCC or legislated by Congress;
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Specific areas in which the FCC should forbear from regulating;
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Specific areas of FCC regulation that Congress should eliminate
or transfer to other agencies; and,
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>The role and specific direction the states should take in
speeding the transition to a competitive digital marketplace.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The project will produce three major written products and three
related events.
<P>
A draft update of the replacement model for the FCC will be produced
by mid-April, 1996.  This first effort will focus on spectrum
and forbearance issues and be timed to inform expected hearings
in the U.S. Senate and House of Representatives on spectrum and
FCC restructuring issues.  It will provide the basis for a PFF
strategic summit in mid-April on the implications of the Telecommunications
Act of 1996.  
<P>
The final draft of the FCC replacement report will be completed
by July 1996, prior to Congress' August recess and the Foundation's
August Aspen Summit, at which the report will be presented and
debated.  
<P>
Finally, an expanded stand-alone report on state regulatory issues
will be completed by November 1996 and released in time to inform
state legislative deliberations in 1997.  State telecommunications
licensing and regulation recommendations will be presented to
state legislative leaders at a winter workshop, perhaps hosted
in conjunction with the American Legislative Exchange Council.
<P>
In addition to these reports and events, the Foundation will maintain
a site on the Internet, at which key issues will be presented
and debated; will arrange expert testimony before appropriate
state and Congressional legislative committees, upon request;
issue Progress on Point alerts, as appropriate; and otherwise
inform the national debate on telecommunications and information
technology policy.
<P>
The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation will provide overall direction
for the project and will have ultimate responsibility for the
final product.  From PFF, the project team will include Dr. George
A. Keyworth, II, Chairman; Dr. Jeffrey Eisenach, President; William
Myers, Vice President for Policy; and Dr. Thomas Lenard, Senior
Fellow and Director of Regulatory Studies.  Peter Pitsch, Esq.,
now an adjunct fellow at PFF, will direct the project.  Participation
of other working group members is expected to provide input on
all important aspects of the project.

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>

